Requester Arguments
===================

Argument Structur
-----------------

   An argument can use absolut values, symbols and registers as
operands and the operators +,-,*,/,|,!,&,<<,>>,~.  Additionally to the
normal symbols, some special symbols are available.

   @{b}*@{ub} By {Argument}.[b,w,l] you can read from a memory address, that is
     defined by the argument. An error is indicated if you specify an
     illegal address with isn't defined in the legal memory space.

   @{b}*@{ub} \#d?  represents the address of the @{b}Disswindows@{ub} with the ID ?

   @{b}*@{ub} \#m?  represents the address of the @{b}Memwindows@{ub} with the ID ?

   @{b}*@{ub} \#c?  represents the address of the @{b}Coppwindows@{ub} with the ID ?

   @{b}*@{ub} \#h?  represents the address of the hunk ?.  Helpful for Enforcer
     and CyberGuard Hunk:Offset output

   @{b}*@{ub} \#ea? represents the address of the EA with the number ?.  Check
     Register Window.

   @{b}*@{ub} \#em? represents the contents where the address EA number ?
     points to.  Check Register Window. If the address EA is illegal an
     error is shown.

   @{b}*@{ub} \#ls  represents the start address of a loaded binary file.

   @{b}*@{ub} \#le  represents the end address of a loaded binary file.

   @{b}*@{ub} \#ll  represents the length address of a loaded binary file.

   @{b}*@{ub} \#p   represents the start address of the programs.  Only true for
     a loaded program.

   If you have the following Enforcer or CyberGuard hit output @{b}Hunk
0:$11c@{ub} you can calculate the address by entering the argument #h0+$11c.


